                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCell" valign="top"><b>Question:</b><br><a href="http://www.earthdawn-classic.com/faqs/selectTopic.html;jsessionid=a0h_bmGHGcIb?id=203974">Earthdawn Players Compendium FAQ</a><br>
                        	      Last Updated By Dammi on 2/9/06
                     </td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCell"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCell"><b>
                           <span style="font-weight: bold; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">This applies only to the first version of the eBook (August 2005)!</span><br
                           />Why is there only one Summon Talent? Elementalists summon elemental                            spirits                 
                           and Nethermancers summon ally spirits - they appear like different talents. How would the                            Summon
                           talent work if a human learned                            it using Versatility?
                           </b></td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCellAlternate" valign="top"><b>Answer:</b></td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCellAlternate"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        The Summon talent is intended to work akin to Thread Weaving (i.e.                            one talent, but different for
                        each Discipline). While the Summoning<br />rules are written to reflect this, we forgot                            to update
                        the Disciplines accordingly. Thus, the following errata apply to the <span style="font-weight: bold;">Player&rsquo;s     
                        Compendium</span>:<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">p.97 - Elementalist, Fifth                            Circle:</span><br
                        />Summon<sup>D</sup> should read Summon (Elemental Spirits)<sup>D</sup><br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">p.110
                        - Nethermancer, Fifth Circle:</span><br />Summon<sup>D</sup>                            should read Summon (Ally Spirits)<sup>D</sup>
                        
                     </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="100%" colspan="3" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        <hr>
                     </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCell" valign="top"><b>Question:</b><br><a href="http://www.earthdawn-classic.com/faqs/selectTopic.html;jsessionid=a0h_bmGHGcIb?id=203974">Earthdawn Players Compendium FAQ</a><br>
                        	      Last Updated By Dammi on 2/9/06
                     </td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCell"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCell"><b>
                           <span style="font-weight: bold; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">This applies only to the first version of the eBook (August 2005)!</span><br
                           />The First Impression talent seems to be broken. It seems way                            too easy to affect other characters.
                           And the effect is permanent!
                           </b></td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCellAlternate" valign="top"><b>Answer:</b></td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCellAlternate"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        Whoops! We intended to align the First Impression talent with the                            Making an Impression mechanics,
                        making a slightly more powerful version (since First Impression is a First Circle talent and                            also
                        available as a skill). Unfortunately, it&rsquo;s a bit over-powered as written.<br /><br />Our apologies.                
                        Here&rsquo;s what we think it should actually look (and work) like. Note: There are no changes to the skill.<br /><br /><span
                        style="font-weight: bold;">(This replaces the entry in both PDF and printed versions of the EDPC)</span><br /><br /><span
                        style="font-weight: bold;">FIRST IMPRESSION</span> (EDPC; p. 184)<br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">Step Number</span>:
                        Rank + Charisma<br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">Action</span>: Yes<br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">Requires Karma</span>:
                        No<br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">Strain</span>: 0<br /><br />The First Impression                            talent
                        allows an adept to favorably impress a gamemaster character he has just met for the first time. The adept makes a First  
                        Impression Test against the target&rsquo;s Social Defense. If the test succeeds, the target character&rsquo;s Attitude improves
                        towards the adept by one degree, for example, a Neutral character becomes Friendly, an Unfriendly character becomes Neutral,
                        and so on. On an Excellent result, it improves by two degrees (see the <span style="font-weight: bold;">Gamemastering    
                        </span>chapter of the <span style="font-weight: bold;">Gamemaster&rsquo;s Compendium</span> for                          
                        more information on Attitudes and how they work). At the gamemaster&rsquo;s discretion, a Pathetic result worsens the character&rsquo;s
                        Attitude by one degree. The new Attitude may be changed for better or worse through future interactions, but reverts back
                        to the original at a rate of one degree per day. Any openly hostile act the adept commits against the impressed character
                        immediately erases the impression. An adept may only attempt to use the First Impression talent once against a given character.
                        
                     </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="100%" colspan="3" class="TableCellAlternate">
